{"type":"message","id":"5520ae69","parentId":"5fd28a73","timestamp":"2026-03-25T20:04:29.411Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking if they can send files through the terminal chat interface, or if there's a workaround. Let me check what I know about OpenClaw's capabilities.\n\nFrom the context, I can see that the user can interact with me through:\n1. Web chat (current interface)\n2. Terminal via `openclaw` command\n\nFor file handling in OpenClaw, I should consider:\n- In the terminal, users can reference file paths directly in their messages\n- I have access to file operations (read, write, edit) in the workspace\n- The terminal interface might not have a direct \"upload\" feature like the web UI, but users can tell me file paths and I can access them\n\nLet me provide a helpful answer about how file sharing works in the terminal interface vs the web interface, and suggest workarounds.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"text","text":"In the terminal, there's no drag-and-drop file upload like the web UI. But you have options:\n\n**For files in your workspace:**\nJust tell me the path and I can read them directly:\n```\nopenclaw \"check this file: ./myfile.txt\"\n```\n\nOr reference them once you're in the interactive session:\n```\n> read the file at C:\\Users\\andre\\Documents\\report.pdf\n```\n\n**For files elsewhere:**\n- Move/copy them to your workspace first, then reference them\n- Or give me the full path if I have access to that location\n\n**Quick workaround:**\nIf you have a file you want me to see and it's sitting somewhere I can't access, just:\n```bash\ncp /path/to/your/file.pdf ~/.openclaw/workspace/\nopenclaw \"check out file.pdf\"\n```\n\nThe web chat is definitely easier for \"here's a random file from my Downloads\" moments. Terminal is better for working with files already in your workspace or projects.\n\nDoes that cover your use case, or are you trying to do something specific with files?"}],